    <h2>Butterfly Clicking vs Jitter Clicking — Which is Better?</h2>
    <p>If you've decided to go beyond regular clicking and want to improve your CPS seriously, you'll face a choice: jitter clicking or butterfly clicking? Both can achieve high CPS, but they're very different in how they work, how long they take to learn, and their long-term viability. Here's everything you need to know.</p>

    <h3>CPS Potential</h3>
    <p><strong>Jitter clicking</strong> typically achieves <strong>10–15 CPS</strong> for practiced users, with exceptional players hitting 16–18 CPS. <strong>Butterfly clicking</strong> commonly achieves <strong>15–25 CPS</strong> for skilled practitioners. On raw CPS ceiling alone, butterfly clicking wins. However, CPS potential varies significantly by individual — some people jitter click faster than others butterfly click.</p>

    <h3>Learning Curve</h3>
    <p>Most people find jitter clicking easier to learn initially, achieving measurable results within a week. The muscle tension concept is simple to grasp even if the execution takes time. Butterfly clicking requires more precise coordination between two fingers and typically takes 3–6 weeks to develop reliable consistency. If you want faster initial results, jitter clicking has the lower learning curve.</p>

    <h3>Physical Comfort and Safety</h3>
    <p>This is where butterfly clicking clearly wins. Jitter clicking involves sustained muscle tension in your forearm, which causes fatigue and, with excessive use, contributes to repetitive strain injuries. Butterfly clicking uses natural alternating finger motion that your fingers perform thousands of times daily during regular typing. Most hand health experts consider butterfly clicking the more sustainable long-term technique.</p>

    <h3>Mouse Compatibility</h3>
    <p>Both techniques work on most gaming mice. However, butterfly clicking is more sensitive to mouse hardware — you need a mouse that can register two rapid presses from different fingers without combining them. Some mice with high debounce times will fail to register butterfly clicks accurately. Jitter clicking is slightly more forgiving of hardware variation.</p>

    <h3>Server Compatibility</h3>
    <p>Most Minecraft servers allow both techniques within their CPS limits. However, butterfly clicking's higher CPS ceiling means it's more likely to trigger anti-cheat than jitter clicking if you're not careful. Both techniques are banned on servers where they can be detected — typically through CPS monitoring above 16–18 CPS.</p>

    <h3>The Verdict — Which Should You Learn?</h3>
    <p>Learn jitter clicking first if: you want faster results, you're primarily playing games where 10–14 CPS is sufficient, or you have limited practice time. Learn butterfly clicking if: you want the highest possible CPS long-term, you're concerned about hand health from jitter clicking, or you're willing to invest 4–6 weeks in the learning curve.</p>
    <p>Many serious competitive players learn both — using jitter clicking as a fallback when fatigued and butterfly clicking when they need maximum output in critical moments.</p>

